Sie blätterte zu einer leeren Seite und notierte das Datum. Darunter schrieb sie „11.5.648–13.12.648“.
„Frischst du alte Erinnerung auf?“, erkundigte sich Ivory und schaute auf das alte Notizbuch. Kari nickte. „Glaubst du, dass sie dich zu Weihnachten rauslassen? Es sind ja nur noch ein paar Tage.“
Kari klopfte zweimal an die Laterne. „Nein“, wie Ivory vermutet hatte. Der Eiskönig ließ Kari niemals hinaus, da er sie als einen „Makel“ betrachtete. Sie kam taub auf die Welt und war die einzige Tochter der Familie, ihre Geschwister waren alle Jungen.
Ähnliches traf auch auf Ivory zu. Als Ivory sich als nichtbinär outete, schien es auch, als würde sich die Welt verändern. Als Strafe für diese Andersartigkeit erhielt Ivory Aufgaben, bei denen man die meiste Zeit allein war.
Außerdem wurde Ivory auch gezwungen, der Prinzessin zu dienen. Es machte Ivory aber nicht viel aus, da Ivory ja auch eine Freundin gewann.
“You're having a birthday soon, right?”, asked Ivory, remembering that the Princess would have her birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad sparkle in her light blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate your birthday?”, asked Ivory, thinking about the last time the Princess had answered this question.
“No”, Kari tapped. Ivory knew this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother banished. Kari was still a baby at the time, but she remembered how agitated the servants and the city residents were. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she could somehow also predict things that would actually happen.
“Well, what do you want to do?”, asked Ivory. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it read:
15 x 15 cm Canvas
Weiß, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
“Should I get these for you?”, Ivory asked the silent Princess whose pigtails swung back and forth due to her vigorous knocking. “Yes?” Ivory chuckled softly. The usually closed-off Princess showed such enthusiasm. It was the first time she asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
“Okay! See you later?”, Ivory asked, stood up, and wriggled her way through the chaos of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bed blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the Princess finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things outside her reach, like Malfarben.
Ivory walked through the corridors again and tried to ignore the whispers of the maidservants.
“I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going into this room.”
“I heard she eats children in this room.”
“She looks like a man, that's not normal, right?”
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the gossip and continued walking. The chamber of the royal painter was located in the east wing behind the second door on the left side.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari's door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six Urdragons that Frostfall allegedly created. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Splatters of paint everywhere, brushes and papers scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different sight greeted her. The entire room was clean, and in front of a red velvet backdrop stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
“Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch your future king being portrayed?”
“Excuse me, little prince,” said Ivory, mostly ignoring him and gathering the items that the quiet princess wished for. “I'm only here to fetch some painting supplies.”
“My little girl wants to leave already?”, asked Aquilo. “But I want you to stay!”
“I don't want to stay either.” Ivory found the painting supplies on the list and placed them in a box. “Besides, I am not a girl.”
The prince, however, had a different opinion. “Oh sweetie, it's just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!” he said vaguely.
“I need to go,” said Ivory, feeling uncomfortable through the prince's response. At that moment, Ivory remembered all the ugly remarks he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past. I just want to leave here.
“Are you leaving already?” Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
“That's no behavior for a future king!” said Ivory.
“No one will find out. People won't believe you, and the painter will keep quiet if his life means anything to him.” He glanced at the painter briefly and then leaned closer to Ivory. “What do you think about a date?” Ivory had been harassed multiple times in the past, but never by a prince and certainly not by the crown prince.
“Do you even know what the word ‘no’ means?” Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away from her.
“No,” answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have everything he desires, doesn't know what the word “no” means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. „Why do you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers,“
„Actually, there are 50,“ he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which whipped around in the cold air.
„Just get it through your head! Why me? I'm a threat to the palace.“ Ivory crossed her arms.
„You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen.“ Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
